    "authority_position": {},
    "audiobook_pre_intro": {
      "why_this_book": "Kai started writing this after observing a specific pattern across the organizations he worked with: the people who burned out fastest were not the people doing the most work. They were the people doing the most unmeasured work. The meetings that existed to coordinate other meetings. The context-switching that no calendar captured. The emotional labor of managing upward, managing laterally, and managing their own responses to environments that were not, by any formal measure, that bad. Nothing in the performance review covered it. Nothing in the job description named it. And so the people experiencing it had no vocabulary for what was happening that did not require them to sound either dramatic or ungrateful. Existing literature on burnout addressed it at the level of symptoms or at the level of organizational reform. Neither was useful for someone inside the machine trying to get through Thursday. Kai wrote this for that person. It does not promise structural change. It offers a way of seeing what is actually happening \u2014 with enough precision that the person inside it can start making decisions that are not purely reactive."
    }
  },
